#### Li-4: Planning Care for Aging
*Strategy:* Research + Navigate
*See also:* H-7: Preparing for End-of-Life Conversations, M-6: Financial Coach (for Social Security and inheritance planning), L-1: Negotiating a Contract (for care facility agreements)
*The Majordomo says:* _There is a period in most people's lives when the person who took care of everything becomes the person who needs care. The role reversal arrives without training, without a manual, and without the emotional infrastructure to handle it. The American system assumes families will figure it out. Other countries built eldercare systems. You have your Agent and the entries that follow._
*The spec:*
::: prompt
I am [beginning to plan for / currently managing] care for
[my parent / relative / spouse] who is [age] and dealing with
[describe the situation: declining mobility, cognitive changes,
recent diagnosis, can no longer live alone, etc.].
My current situation:
— Where they live now: [with me / alone / assisted living / other]
— Their financial situation: [brief — pension, savings, Medicare,
   Medicaid, none of these]
— What help they currently have: [family, home aide, none]
— What is changing or has changed: [the specific trigger]
Please help me:
1. Understand what level of care they may need now and next
2. What programs or benefits they may qualify for
3. What legal documents should be in place if they aren't already
4. What decisions I should NOT delay
:::
*What to do with the output:* Make a list of the time-sensitive items — power of attorney, healthcare proxy, benefit applications — and do those first. The emotional work is real but the paperwork has deadlines. See H-7 for the conversation itself.

::: tip
_"My [parent] has [condition] and [Medicare/Medicaid/no insurance]. What is the single most important thing I should do this week that I am probably not doing?"_ — Start with the gap you don't know about.
:::


::: fairness
Eldercare resources vary enormously by state. Ask your Agent to be specific to your state and county. Federal programs are the floor, not the ceiling.
:::


<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: Caregiver burden statistics. AARP/NAC 2020 survey shows 53 million Americans are unpaid caregivers. Average caregiver spends 24+ hours/week on care. Financial cost to family caregivers estimated at $522 billion/year in unpaid labor. These numbers are staggering and undersold. Verify all figures against most recent data. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): "Anticipatory grief" — the grief that begins before a person dies, while they are still present but diminishing. Rando (2000) has the foundational work. Caregivers experience grief, guilt, resentment, and love simultaneously, and the cultural expectation is that they should feel only the last one. The sandwich generation — caring for children and parents at the same time — is underresearched as a distinct psychological phenomenon despite affecting millions. Schulz & Sherwood (2008) in American Journal of Geriatric Psychiatry found caregiver mortality risk increases 63%. Caregiving is literally life-shortening. This needs its own callout. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The gender disparity in caregiving is one of the most consistent findings in the literature. Women provide approximately 75% of unpaid eldercare (NAC/AARP). This is not accidental — it is the result of structural expectations that predate and outlast any individual family. The entry should name this without prescribing guilt or resentment. It just is, and your Agent can help you navigate it regardless of your gender. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: Long-term care costs. Genworth 2023 Cost of Care Survey — median cost of a private nursing home room is approximately $9,733/month. Home health aide approximately $5,720/month. Most people do not have this money. The gap between what care costs and what families can pay is the defining financial crisis of aging in America, and most people encounter it for the first time at a moment of maximum emotional vulnerability. -->

::: science
Medicaid is the primary payer for long-term care in the United States, but qualifying requires near-poverty. The "spend-down" — depleting assets to meet eligibility thresholds — is the mechanism most families encounter. The five-year lookback period means gifts or transfers made within five years of application trigger penalties. The One Big Beautiful Bill Act (2025) added new constraints: a $1 million home equity cap for long-term care eligibility starting in 2028, retroactive coverage reduced from 90 to 30 days before application, and six-month eligibility reverification. Asset limits, exempt property, and spousal protections vary significantly by state — ask your Agent for the current rules in yours.[^li4-1]
:::


[^li4-1]: KFF, ["Health Provisions in the 2025 Federal Budget Reconciliation Law."](https://www.kff.org/medicaid/health-provisions-in-the-2025-federal-budget-reconciliation-law/) See also [Medicaid.gov](https://www.medicaid.gov/) for state-specific eligibility thresholds and the five-year lookback rules.

