#### Li-9: Making a Household Budget That Holds
*Strategy:* Draft + Decide
*See also:* M-6: Financial Coach, Ho-6: Understanding Your Utility Bill
*The Majordomo says:* _Budgeting advice assumes the problem is discipline. For most households, the problem is math — income that does not cover expenses, no matter how disciplined the allocation. Your Agent will not lecture you about lattes. It will help you see where the money actually goes, identify the three largest levers you can pull, and build a plan that survives contact with reality._
*The spec:*
::: prompt
I want to build a household budget that actually works.
My situation:
— Monthly income (after taxes): [amount]
— Number of people in household: [X]
— Biggest expenses I know about: [rent, car, childcare, debt, etc.]
— What I'm struggling with: [running out before payday /
   can't save anything / don't know where it goes / debt spiral /
   one emergency away from crisis]
Please:
1. Help me categorize my spending into needs, wants, and debts
2. Identify the 2-3 biggest levers I have — the places where
   a change would make the most difference
3. Build a realistic monthly plan that includes some flexibility
   — a plan I'll actually follow, not an ideal I'll abandon
4. Tell me honestly: is this a budgeting problem or an income problem?
:::
*What to do with the output:* Track actual spending for one month before adjusting the budget. Most people are surprised by at least one category. Ask your Agent: _"Here's what I actually spent last month: [list]. How does this compare to the plan, and what's the one change that would have the biggest impact?"_

::: science
Mullainathan & Shafir (2013) document "scarcity mindset" — financial stress reduces cognitive bandwidth by the equivalent of 13 IQ points, making financial decisions harder precisely when they matter most.[^li9-1]
:::


<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: Mullainathan & Shafir (2013) "Scarcity: Why Having Too Little Means So Much." The 13 IQ points figure comes from Mani et al. (2013) in Science. The specific methodology has faced some replication questions, but the core finding — poverty taxes cognition — is robust even if the exact magnitude is debated. Verify current status of the replication. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The moral framing of debt and budgeting is one of the most harmful information asymmetries in personal finance. The entire "personal responsibility" framework for household budgets ignores that real wages have been flat since roughly 1979 while housing, healthcare, education, and childcare have outpaced inflation by multiples. The reader who can't make the numbers work is not failing at budgeting — they are succeeding at arithmetic. The entry should state this plainly without becoming a polemic. This is the Conners' problem (see Money intro) restated in 2024 dollars. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): Financial shame and secrecy between partners is the strongest predictor of relationship conflict about money (Britt et al., 2017). Couples fight about money more than any other topic (Dew et al., 2012) and it is the second leading cause of divorce. The budget is not just a spreadsheet — it is a document that reveals values, fears, and power dynamics within the household. Building a budget together is a relationship act, not just a financial one. Cross-reference Li-1 (Difficult Conversations). The entry should acknowledge this without turning into couples therapy. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The "emergency fund" advice — keep 3-6 months of expenses in savings — is correct and mathematically impossible for the roughly 60% of Americans who cannot cover a $1,000 emergency (Bankrate, annual survey — verify latest year). The entry should acknowledge the gap between sound financial advice and the economic reality of the reader. "Save more" is accurate. It is also useless if the math doesn't work. The useful version is: "Here is the order to build financial resilience when you have very little margin." Your Agent can build that sequence. -->

[^li9-1]: Mullainathan, S. & Shafir, E. (2013). _Scarcity: Why Having Too Little Means So Much._ Times Books.

