#### Li-10: Learn a language
*Strategy:* Research + Navigate (Expert Role)
*See also:* Li-5: Planning Trips (for travel-specific language prep)
*The Majordomo says:* _Language immersion programs cost thousands of dollars. [Duolingo](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Duolingo) is free and teaches you how to say “the elephant drinks milk” in seventeen languages. Private tutors charge $40 to $80 per hour and are available when their schedule permits. Your Agent is available now, infinitely patient, never visibly disappointed when you conjugate the same verb wrong for the fifth time, and will have an actual conversation with you about the things you actually need to say — not the things a textbook thinks you should practice._
*The spec:*
::: prompt
Act as a patient language tutor for [language].
My current level: [complete beginner / basic phrases / conversational]
My goal: [travel / family communication / work / general learning]
What I struggle with most: [pronunciation / grammar / vocabulary /
understanding native speakers]
How would you suggest we work together in our conversations?
:::
*What to do with the output:* Start using it immediately. Language learning research consistently shows that production — trying to say things, getting them wrong, trying again — beats passive study. Your Agent can do something no textbook can: respond to what you say, correct you in real time, and adjust the difficulty to where you actually are rather than where a curriculum assumes you should be.

*Common language Expert Role specs:*
::: prompt
I’m traveling to [country] in [timeframe]. Teach me the 20 phrases
that will make the biggest difference — greetings, ordering food,
asking for help, being polite. Prioritize what locals actually
appreciate hearing from visitors.
:::
::: prompt
I’m trying to reconnect with [language] that my [parent/grandparent]
spoke. I understand some when I hear it but I can’t produce it.
Start me where I am, not at the beginning.
:::
::: prompt
I need to [give a presentation / attend a meeting / make small talk]
in [language] for work. My level is [X]. Help me prepare
the specific phrases and responses I’ll need.
:::

::: tip
_”Pretend you’re a [waiter / taxi driver / shopkeeper / colleague] in [city] and only respond in [language]. If I get stuck, give me the phrase I need, then let me try again.”_ — Role-play with your Agent is the closest thing to immersion without a plane ticket.
:::


::: science
Krashen’s [input hypothesis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Input%5Fhypothesis) (1982) argues that language acquisition happens when learners receive input slightly above their current level — “i+1.” Your Agent can calibrate to exactly this level in real time, something classroom instruction cannot do for 25 students simultaneously. The evidence for comprehensible input as the primary driver of acquisition is among the most replicated findings in applied linguistics.[^li10-1]
:::


::: fairness
Your Agent’s language ability varies by language. It is strongest in English, Mandarin, Spanish, French, German, and Japanese. For less-resourced languages — many Indigenous languages, regional dialects, signed languages — its accuracy drops significantly. If you are working in a less common language, verify key phrases with a native speaker or community resource. Your Agent will tell you when it is less confident if you ask.
:::


<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: Language learning apps market is approximately $15B globally. Efficacy data is sparse and mostly self-reported. Duolingo’s own research (Vesselinov & Grego, 2012) found 34 hours of Duolingo was equivalent to one university semester of Spanish — but the comparison is a low bar and the study was industry-funded. The honest assessment: apps build vocabulary and habit, but conversation fluency requires conversation. Your Agent provides the conversation piece that apps lack. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): Heritage language loss — second-generation immigrants who understand but can’t speak their parents’ language — is one of the most common and least discussed forms of cultural grief. Fillmore (2000) “Loss of Family Languages” documents how English immersion policies systematically severed linguistic continuity. The reader who wants to reconnect with a heritage language is doing something emotionally loaded, not just intellectually interesting. The entry should honor that without making it heavy. Your Agent won’t replace a grandmother’s accent, but it can help you rebuild the grammar that time eroded. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The shame of not speaking a language “you should know” — whether heritage, professional, or social — is a real barrier to starting. Adults are measurably worse at language learning than children (critical period hypothesis, Lenneberg 1967, contested but partially supported) and also measurably more self-conscious about errors. The Agent’s key advantage is that it eliminates the social risk of looking foolish. This is not trivial — it is the primary barrier for adult learners. -->

[^li10-1]: Krashen, S.D. (1982). _Principles and Practice in Second Language Acquisition._ Pergamon Press.

