#### Li-11: Escaping Social Media
*Strategy:* Research + Decide
*See also:* Li-7: Raising Kids (for the screen time conversation), Li-8: Wellness Coach (for compulsive behavior patterns)
*The Majordomo says:* _The discourse says “screen time.” The research says “social media.” These are not the same variable. Using the internet to learn how a carburetor works is a different neurological event than scrolling a feed engineered to make you feel slightly worse about yourself at intervals calibrated to keep you scrolling. One is the most capable self-education infrastructure ever built. The other is an engagement-optimization engine that colonized it. The intervention is not less internet. It is better internet._

*The spec:*
::: prompt
I want to reduce my social media use [or help my kid reduce theirs].
My current situation:
— Platforms I use most: [list them]
— How much time I estimate I spend: [hours/day]
— What I get out of it: [connection, news, entertainment, habit, nothing]
— What it costs me: [time, mood, sleep, focus, comparison anxiety]
— What I’ve tried: [app limits, deleting apps, cold turkey, nothing]
Please help me:
1. Understand the difference between purposeful internet use
   and engagement-optimized consumption
2. Identify which of my current habits are serving me and which aren’t
3. Build a realistic reduction plan that doesn’t require
   willpower I don’t have — change the cues, not the person
4. Suggest what to replace the habit with — the gap needs filling
   or the habit comes back
:::
*What to do with the output:* Start with one platform. The one that makes you feel worst, or the one that eats the most time. Remove it from your phone — not your life, just your pocket. You can still use it on a computer, which introduces enough friction to break the automatic-checking loop. The research is clear: the harm concentrates in compulsive mobile checking, not in deliberate use.

::: science
A landmark study in the _American Economic Review_ exploited Facebook’s staggered rollout across U.S. college campuses as a natural experiment. College-wide Facebook access caused a 7% increase in severe depression and a 20% increase in anxiety disorders — effects roughly one-fifth the magnitude of losing a job. The mechanism is not use itself but emotional dependency: routine use correlates with positive outcomes, while compulsive checking driven by fear of missing out correlates negatively across every measure.[^li11-1]
:::


::: science
The distinction between purposeful and passive internet use is not a value judgment — it is a measurable difference. Research on primary school students found that using the internet to search for information favors educational outcomes, while social network use hinders them. These are categorically different activities, not points on a single spectrum.[^li11-2]
:::


::: meme
The web evolved from text to graphics to audio to video to interactive simulation — mapping almost precisely onto the full range of human learning modalities. Then social media arrived and replaced “learn anything” with “react to everything.” The infrastructure is still there. The feeds are in the way. Moving the feeds is the project.
:::


::: fairness
“Just delete it” is advice that ignores the people for whom social media is their primary connection to community — isolated caregivers, people with disabilities, immigrants maintaining ties to home. The goal is not abstinence. The goal is shifting the ratio from reactive to purposeful. Ask your Agent: _”I need social media for [specific reason]. Help me keep that function and reduce the rest.”_
:::


<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: Verify all citations from the research brief. Yale 2026 study, Braghieri et al. in AER, Bekalu et al. at Harvard, Surgeon General’s Advisory 2023. The evidence base is strong but the specific figures need current verification. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The Surgeon General declared loneliness an epidemic (2023) and social media a risk to youth mental health (2023) — in the same year. These are not contradictions. Social media promises connection and delivers comparison. The loneliest generation in measured history is also the most connected in network terms. The paradox is the product feature, not the bug. Turkle (2011, “Alone Together”) identified this early. The research has caught up. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED (HUMAN CONDITION): The addictive design patterns in social media — variable-ratio reinforcement schedules, social validation feedback loops, infinite scroll — are not accidental. Aza Raskin (inventor of infinite scroll) has publicly stated he regrets the design. Tristan Harris (former Google design ethicist) founded the Center for Humane Technology on the premise that these patterns are deliberately engineered. The reader should know that their difficulty quitting is not a personal failure. It is a design outcome. -->

<!-- RESEARCH NEEDED: Practical intervention evidence. The most effective interventions are environmental, not motivational: removing apps from phones, using website blockers, setting physical phone-free zones. Hunt et al. (2018, Journal of Social and Clinical Psychology) found that limiting social media to 30 minutes/day significantly reduced loneliness and depression. The intervention was small. The effect was not. -->

[^li11-1]: Braghieri, L., Levy, R., & Makarin, A. “Social Media and Mental Health.” _American Economic Review._ See also Bekalu, M.A. et al. (2020) at Harvard T.H. Chan School of Public Health on the routine-vs-compulsive use distinction.

[^li11-2]: Prieto-Latorre, C. et al. (2022). “Internet use and academic performance: An interval approach.” _Education and Information Technologies._ See also Firth, J. et al. (2019). “The ‘online brain’: how the Internet may be changing our cognition.” _World Psychiatry._

